Solution: MVP

Alberto Miño
on Jun 22

Hi Arjan and team, I comed up with this solution:

**********Start code***************
from __future__ import annotations
from typing import IO
import tkinter as tk
import tkinter.filedialog as fd
import tkinter.messagebox as mb

import pandas as pd
from app import process_data

class Model:
def __init__(self) -> None:
self.data: pd.DataFrame = pd.DataFrame()
self.processed_data: pd.DataFrame = pd.DataFrame()

def load_data(self, file_path: str) -> None:
self.data = pd.read_csv(file_path)

class Presenter:
def __init__(self, model: Model, view: View) -> None:
self.model = model
self.view = view

def load_csv(self):
# Code to load the CSV file
file_path: str = self.view.get_csv_file_path()
self.model.load_data(file_path)
self.view.show_info("Import", "Data successfully loaded!")

def show_input_data(self) -> None:
self.view.show_data(self.model.data)

def analyze_data(self):
if self.model.data.empty:
self.view.show_error("Error", "Please load data first!")
return
self.model.processed_data = process_data(self.model.data, self.view.selected_option.get())
self.view.show_data(self.model.processed_data)

def export_data(self):
file_path = self.view.get_save_file_path()
if file_path is not None:
self.model.processed_data.to_csv(file_path, index=False)
self.view.show_info("Export", "Data exported successfully!")

def run(self) -> None:
# Create the main window
self.view.init_ui(self)
# Start the main loop
self.view.mainloop()

class View(tk.Tk):
def __init__(self) -> None:
super().__init__()
self.title("Data Processing GUI")

def get_csv_file_path(self):
# Code to get the file path to the CSV file.
file_path: str = fd.askopenfilename(filetypes=[("CSV Files", "*.csv")])
return file_path

def get_save_file_path(self) -> IO | None:
file_path = fd.asksaveasfile(
defaultextension=".csv", filetypes=[("CSV Files", "*.csv")]
)
return file_path

def show_info(self, title: str, message: str) -> None:
# Helper function to show info to the user.
mb.showinfo(title, message)

def show_error(self, title: str, message: str) -> None:
# Helper function to show info to the user.
mb.showerror(title, message)

def show_data(self, data: pd.DataFrame) -> None:
# Clear widget from previous data
self.text_widget.delete("1.0", tk.END)
try:
# Set the text of the widget to the data
self.text_widget.insert(tk.END, str(data))
except NameError:
self.show_info("Error", "No data to show!")

def init_ui(self, presenter: Presenter) -> None:

# Create the widgets for the GUI
self.load_button = tk.Button(self, text="Load CSV", command=presenter.load_csv)
self.show_input_data_button = tk.Button(
self, text="Show input data", command=presenter.show_input_data
)
self.analyze_button = tk.Button(self, text="Analyze Data", command=presenter.analyze_data)
# Create a variable to store the selected option
self.selected_option = tk.StringVar(self)
# Create a list of options
self.options = ["All", "Temperature", "Humidity", "CO2"]
# Set the default selected option
self.selected_option.set(self.options[0])
# Create an OptionMenu widget
self.option_menu = tk.OptionMenu(self, self.selected_option, *self.options)

self.export_button = tk.Button(self, text="Export Data", command=presenter.export_data)
# Create a Text widget to display the data
self.text_widget = tk.Text(self)

# Arrange the widgets in the main window
self.text_widget.pack(side=tk.BOTTOM)
self.load_button.pack(side=tk.LEFT)
self.show_input_data_button.pack(side=tk.LEFT)
self.analyze_button.pack(side=tk.LEFT)
self.option_menu.pack(side=tk.LEFT)
self.export_button.pack(side=tk.LEFT)

def main() -> None:
model = Model()
view = View()
presenter = Presenter(model, view)
presenter.run()

if __name__ == "__main__":
main()

**********End code***************
I really enjoyed this one, it was a really good "refactoring exercise" and also i had never worked with tKinter :)

Cheers!

Wiktor Góra
on Dec 16, 2023

Hi Arjan,
I have the impression that the approach you presented in your Youtube video and in the video on this course are different from each other. In the Youtube video, the Presenter class is sort of the "master". It is where the logic of what the data flow is and what is presented to the user and when. The View class, as the name suggests, only presents and retrieves data to the user and handles triggers. In the course video, on the other hand, the View class takes over this responsibility. Not only does it contain the application logic, but it is also responsible for exception handling. In this case, the Presenter class seems to be an unnecessary middleware. On the other hand, in the course video you said that it is good for the Presenter class to have as little connection to the View class as possible, which makes a lot of sense with an approach where View has the role of "master". Hence my question, which approach is the better one, or is it "depends" as usual?

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Dec 18, 2023

Hi Wiktor, there is unfortunately no "ground truth" for how application logic should be distributed over view and presenter. Some application logic is going to be very view-dependent, such as changing button states in on_load_csv_button_click. In this case to me it makes more sense to keep that as part of the view in order to minimize communication. Loading and interpreting a csv file though makes more sense to me as part of the Presenter since that has little to do with the view/UI. In the end, it's about deciding where something fits best conceptually, so that's what I tried to do in this solution.

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Apr 25

Hi Philipp, certainly the View is going to be dependent on the result of actions performed by the Presenter. You can still do that, even if the application logic is in the presenter. In your code that is actually what happens: the presenter has a 'handle_load_csv' method that does the actual task of loading the file (or actually delegating that to the model). To clarify the difference between that method and the 'load_csv' method in the View, I would call the method in the view 'select_csv_file', since that doesn't actually load a CSV file, but only selects it.

REPLY
Karol Borkowski
on Aug 26, 2023

Isn't it cleaner if the presenter doesn't depend on the view at all? The view would just call the presenter's functions fetching analyzed and formatted data, which are ready to be displayed. The display would be handled by the view, which could also be replaced without changing a single line in the presenter.
Additionally, there is no need to store a copy (or a reference) of the data in the view. We create an unnecessary dependency on pandas when everything the view needs is strings.
What do you think?

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Sep 5, 2023

Hi Karol, it would be cleaner if the presenter wouldn't depend on the view at all. However, unfortunately the communication between view and presenter is often bidirectional. The view needs a reference to the presenter, so that if the user presses a button, the view can tell the presenter that some business logic should be executed. And the other way around: if there's a change in the model (a new data set is available) or an event occurs such as "data export completed", then the presenter needs to update the view (show a notification or update a text/status field).

For your second point, yes, if the view only needs strings that does simplify things and you don't need the pandas dependency. I left the pandas dependency because I thought it might make sense in the future if - for example - you want to display data in a table and have basic filtering/sorting options, for which pandas can be helpful.

REPLY
Eduardo Motta de Moraes
on Sep 7, 2023

If I may add my 2 cents to the topic, the idea of having the view call the presenter functions to get the data sounded tempting at first to me too.

But I think it would actually make the view more coupled with the presenter: the view would need to know about the presenter implementation details, so replacing the view in the future would require taking that into account.

On the other hand, if we maintain the proposed architecture, with the presenter calling view functions to update the gui, we can abstract the view with an interface to ensure decoupling.

What do you think, Arjan (and anyone else who wants to comment)? Does that make sense?

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Sep 7, 2023

Hi Eduardo, it's definitely a good option to put an abstraction layer between the view and the presenter. That could even go both ways where you define a protocol for both the view and the presenter, so that neither knows implementation details of the other.

REPLY
Michael Brittain
on Jul 13, 2023

The presenter object isn't initialised in the View when the view is created. This raises an unresolved attribute error in the methods that reference self.presenter.

I'm wondering if there is another approach. I originally started with a create_ui function, that received the presenter as an argument. The UI elements are then bound directly to functions within the presenter when they are initialised in the create_ui function.

The downside is there are then further callbacks to handle the message box calls within the view ... which I guess is the reason that you created the wrapper functions within the view instead and bound those to the UI elements instead.

Still, it seems a little strange to patch the view object after creation with "view.presenter = presenter"

REPLY
Arjan Egges
on Jul 18, 2023

Hi Michael, there's often a "bootstrapping" issue with architectures like MVC and MVP. In many cases, the view or the presenter/controller needs the other object in order to properly initialize itself. In this particular case, the presenter needs the view because it needs to send updates and the view needs the presenter, because it needs to attach callbacks. So this was my solution.

Perhaps another option is that the presenter calls a "register" method in the view and passes itself so that the view can then attach the presenter to the callbacks. But I'm not sure it will lead to cleaner code than simply supplying the presenter to the view to establish the connection.
